Vsearch_Strategy: first I looked at the half that had all the lines tilting in one direction, more or less 45 degrees to the left. As with my eyes resting, taking that area in, I could usually spot the single line facing exactly 90 degrees opposite to these within a second or two. If there was no target in that half, I started scanning the "scattered" area for a target. This I found more difficult, and I used two or three different strategies trying to improve my time and my ability to spot the target (if it was present). Either by trying to pick a comparison point (a line facing 45 degrees to the left), that I can compare the lines to that were tilting to the right, but I wasn't sure about their angle, as the scattered lines around them felt like they created an optical illusion. Another strategy used for the "scattered area" was going through it row by row, which I changed to coloumn by coloumn towards the end. It felt helpful to my brain to switch up my search pattern.
Bucket_Strategy: At first, I just concentrated on fulfilling the task: getting each bucket to the indicated spot. However, on the first try, when I walked to the second bucket, it occured to me that this could be done in a more efficient way, in terms of preserving energy (only lifting them when necessary and taking as few steps as possible): so I walked to the further bucket, picked it up with my dominant hand then picked up the second bucket on the way back. This seemed the most efficient way, at least, I couldn't think of anything more efficient so I stuck to this method throughout the rest of the "runs".

Bucket_Strategy: I steadily walked over to the buckets In order i.e. approached the bucket nearest to me, picked it up in my right hand after bending down to reach it, then approached the bucket further away and picked it up in my left hand, with the same steady, consistent motions and pace of walking, and finally carried both buckets at the same distance from the ground while walking back. I put the buckets down next to each other at the same time in the center of the yellow block. I used this same strategy each time.
